slides_data.notes: Hi there! This is a quick byte on if / else statements.
☑️ Do This: Review the purpose and syntax of an if statement.

☑️ Do This: Recall the syntax of an if statement.

🎙️ Say: We already know how this part works. The Painter checks whether it's on a bucket. If that's true, it takes the paint. This part is a one-way selection – something happens only if the condition is true.

☑️ Do This: Introduce the else statement. Emphasize that the else gives the program a second path – something to do if the if is skipped.

🎙️ Say: Now we're adding something new: the keyword else. This tells the program "If the condition is false, do this instead."

Compare it to a real-life example (e.g., "If I finish my homework, I'll go outside. Else, I’ll stay in and work.")

☑️ Do This: Emphasize how only one branch of the if/else will run.

🎙️ Say: This is the else block. The program only runs this line if the Painter is not on a bucket. If the condition is false, it skips the if block and runs the else block instead.

☑️ Do This: Remind students that the code needs to be indented just like with functions, while loops, and if statements.

🎙️ Say: Just like with if statements, the else block also needs to be indented. That tells the computer what belongs to that branch of the code.

scenes.speech: Hi there! This is a quick byte on if-else statements.
scenes.elevenlabs: [warmly welcoming] Hi there! This is a quick byte on if-else statements.

scenes.comment: Explains the purpose and syntax of an if statement.
scenes.speech: An if statement lets your program make a decision. It checks a condition. If that condition is true, the code inside the if block runs. If the condition is false, the program skips that block and does nothing.
scenes.elevenlabs: [patiently] An if statement lets your program make a decision. It checks a condition. [deliberate] If that condition is true, the code inside the if block runs. [clarifying] If the condition is false, the program skips that block and does nothing.

scenes.comment: Defines two-way selection using an if/else statement.
scenes.speech: Two-way selection, also known as an if-else statement, is when your program chooses one path or the other depending on the condition.
scenes.elevenlabs: [explaining] Two-way selection, also known as an if-else statement, is when your program chooses one path or the other depending on the condition.
